{"cursor":"3081","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Antonio \"ToÃ±o\" Salazar' (June 1897 - December 1986) was a Salvadoran\ncaricaturist, illustrator and diplomat. Born in Santa Tecla, in 1920 he went to\nstudy in Mexico on an art scholarship then in 1922 traveled to France to join\nthe throng of artists and writers from around the world who were living,\nworking, and learning in the Montparnasse Quarter of Paris.\n\nSalazar became friends with Mexican writer/diplomat JosÃ© MarÃ­a GonzÃ¡lez de\nMendoza and the Guatemalan writer Luis Cardoza y AragÃ³n. He did the\nillustrations for AragÃ³n's 1923 book Luna Park. A leftist, in the 1930s he\nworked as a propagandist for the Republican cause in Spain. During World War II\nhe went to Buenos Aires where he was employed as an illustrator and caricaturist\nat the socialist weekly magazine Argentina Libre. Salazar published satires of\nAdolf Hitler, General Franco, Benito Mussolini and Argentina's rising star, Juan\nPerÃ³n. The right-wing government closed Argentina Libre and Salazar was forced\nto leave the country. He traveled to Montevideo, Uruguay where he remained until\n1949 when he was allowed back into Buenos Aires for a time.\n\nIn the early 1950s, the new El Salvador government of President Ãscar Osorio\ngave ToÃ±o Salazar a diplomatic appointment in Montevideo. He spent twenty years\nserving in various consulate offices in Uruguay, France, Italy, and Israel. In\n1978, his country awarded him the [[Order of JosÃ© MatÃ­as Delgado]] and the\nPremio Nacional de Cultura.\n\nToÃ±o Salazar died in 1986 in San Salvador from Parkinson's disease. A\nsignificant collection of his work is at the El Salvador Museum of Art in San\nSalvador who held a major exhibition of his works in 2005 and who named a\nreception hall in his honor.\n\nToÃ±o Salazar's work was a strong influence on the Cuban caricaturist Juan David.\n","linknr":119,"url":"Toño_Salazar","recorded":1375084406,"links":["/w/index.php?title=To%C3%